**Comparing Strings in Java**

To compare strings in Java, use the `.equals()` method instead of the `==` operator.

### Why?

The `==` operator checks if two strings refer to the same object in memory. This is not what we want when comparing strings for equality.

### When to Use `.equals()` vs `==`

- Use `.equals()` to compare the values of two strings.
- Use `==` to compare references to objects.

### Key Differences

- `.equals()` compares the values of two strings.
- `==` compares the references of two objects.

### Example

```java
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

// Use .equals() to compare the values of str1 and str2
if (str1.equals(str2)) {
  System.out.println("The strings are equal.");
} else {
  System.out.println("The strings are not equal.");
}

// Use == to compare the references of str1 and str2
if (str1 == str2) {
  System.out.println("The references are equal.");
} else {
  System.out.println("The references are not equal.");
}
```

